"1530–1559":"1530–1559","1556–1590":"1556–1590","1525–1576":"1525–1576","1525":"1525","13 April 1525":"13 April 1525","1556":"1556","1576":"1576","1530":"1530","08 December 1576":"8 December 1576","1590":"1590","1559":"1559","Brewood, Staffordshire, Kingdom of England":"Brewood, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Gunston Hall, Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fowke,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: relationship name from the Middle English, Anglo-Norman French personal name  <i>Folk</i>,  <i>Fulk</i>,  <i>Fuke</i>.  Compare  Foxon  . For a variant form of the personal name  see  Foulkes  .  See also  Fudge  , which may sometimes be a variant form."],"variants":[{"name":"Fudge","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English, Anglo-Norman French personal name <i>Fulch</i> or <i>Fuche</i>, usually a pet form of Old French <i>Fulcher</i>, <i>Fucher</i> (see   Fulcher  ). Voicing of ‘ch’ to soft ‘g’ gave rise to <i>Fudge</i>. The name may sometimes have been interchangeable with <b>Fowke</b> (for which see   Foulk   1), derived from a pet form of this and other Old French personal names in <i>Fulc-</i>.","English: habitational name from Fuge, in Blackawton, Devon. This placename is composed of Old English <i>feoh</i> ‘cattle’ + <i>wīc</i> ‘farm, dairy farm, village’."]},{"name":"Folke","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Fowke  ."]},{"name":"Fook","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Fowke  ."]},{"name":"Foulk","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English and Anglo-Norman French personal name <i>Fulk</i>, which is of ancient Germanic origin, ultimately from an element meaning ‘folk, people’."]},{"name":"Fogg","meanings":["English (northern): possibly a variant of <b>Fowke</b> (see   Foulk   1). It may derive from Middle English <i>fogge</i> ‘aftermath’ (i.e. grass left to grow after the hay has been cut, also applied to long grass in a water meadow), especially in northern England, where the term occurs as a specifying element in minor placenames, but as it is not found on its own as a simplex name, the derivation is doubtful without some supporting evidence. The word <i>fogge</i>, which is probably of Old Norse origin, is still in use as a dialect term in Craven, Yorkshire, and in eastern Lancashire. modern English <i>fog</i> ‘thick mist’ is first attested in the 16th century and is unlikely to be the source of the surname."]},{"name":"Fuke","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Fowke   and  compare  Fook  ."]},{"name":"Folk","meanings":["German: variant of   Volk   1 and, in North America, also an altered form of this. This form of the surname is also found in Czechia.","English: variant of   Foulk   1."]},{"name":"Focke","meanings":["North German, East Frisian, and Dutch: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Folco</i>, a pet form of various names beginning with <i>Folc-</i> or <i>Volk-</i>; cognate with   Foulk   1.","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Foulk   1. See also   Foulks  ."]},{"name":"Foulke","meanings":["English (Derbyshire and Shropshire): variant of   Foulk  ."]},{"name":"Fulk","meanings":["English: variant of   Foulk   1.","Altered form of German   Volk   or   Falk  ."]}]},{"name":"5th","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Swiss German: possibly from a short form of surnames formed with <i>Id-</i>, <i>Ith-</i>, the root of ancient Germanic origin, of disputed etymology, possibly cognate with Old Norse <i>idh</i> ‘work, activity’.","Cambodian: written អ៊ិត, unexplained."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Lord","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>laford</i>, <i>louerd</i>, <i>lord</i> ‘lord, master’ (Old English <i>hlāford</i>), perhaps given to a someone who played the part of the lord or master of ceremonies in festival games.","Irish: adoption of the English name (see 1 above) as a translation of the main element of Gaelic <b>Ó Tighearnaigh</b> (see   Tierney  ) and <b>Mac Thighearnáin</b> (see   McKiernan  ).","Americanized form of French <b>Laure</b>, a variant of the personal name   Laur   3."],"variants":[{"name":"Tierney","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Eamon, John Patrick, Brigid, Clodagh, Kieran, Michael Sean, Siobhan.","Irish: shortened form of <b>O'Tierney</b>, an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Tíghearnaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Tighearnach</i>’, a byname meaning ‘lord, master’. The Gaelic name is sometimes ‘translated’ as English   Lord  . Compare   Tiernan  ."]},{"name":"Lords","meanings":["English: variant of   Lord  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]},{"name":"Bradshaw","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the three places called Bradshaw in Lancashire, Yorkshire, and Derbyshire, from Old English <i>brād</i> ‘broad’ + <i>sceaga</i> ‘thicket’."],"variants":[{"name":"Brayshaw","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): variant of   Bradshaw  , reflecting the local Yorkshire pronunciation."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Roger Bradshaw Fowke, 5th Lord Brewood was born on 13 April 1525. He had at least 1 daughter with Margaret Mary Moreton of Haughton-Fowke. He died on 8 December 1576, at the age of 51."},"et":{"13 April 1525–08 December 1576":"13. aprill 1525–8. detsember 1576","1530–1559":"1530–1559","1556–1590":"1556–1590","1525–1576":"1525–1576","1525":"1525","13 April 1525":"13. aprill 1525","1556":"1556","1576":"1576","1530":"1530","08 December 1576":"8. detsember 1576","1590":"1590","1559":"1559","Brewood, Staffordshire, Kingdom of England":"Brewood, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Gunston Hall, Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"13 April 1525–08 December 1576":"13. huhtikuuta 1525–8. joulukuuta 1576","1530–1559":"1530–1559","1556–1590":"1556–1590","1525–1576":"1525–1576","1525":"1525","13 April 1525":"13. huhtikuuta 1525","1556":"1556","1576":"1576","1530":"1530","08 December 1576":"8. joulukuuta 1576","1590":"1590","1559":"1559","Brewood, Staffordshire, Kingdom of England":"Brewood, Staffordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Gunston Hall, Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"13 April 1525–08 December 1576":"13 avril 1525–8 décembre 1576","1530–1559":"1530–1559","1556–1590":"1556–1590","1525–1576":"1525–1576","1525":"1525","13 April 1525":"13 avril 1525","1556":"1556","1576":"1576","1530":"1530","08 December 1576":"8 décembre 1576","1590":"1590","1559":"1559","Brewood, Staffordshire, Kingdom of England":"Brewood, Staffordshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Gunston Hall, Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, Angleterre, Royaum